title: Grateful Dead Live at Autzen Stadium, U. of Oregon on 1993-08-21
description: Here Comes Sunshine, Walkin' Blues, Lazy River Road, Queen Jane Approximately, Bird Song, Promised Land China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, Way To Go Home, Truckin'-> Good Morning Little School Girl*-> Smokestack Lightning*-> Drums-> Space-> Jam-> The Last Time*-> Standing On the Moon E: One More Saturday Night, E: I Fought The Law

reviews.review_text:
Missing Oregon Trail Mix intro Has anyone seen the missing Oregon trail Mix intro that the Band did on this day. 
Love to get a complete source for this sweet show

Back From A Break Pretty ordinary show - no frills, no spills. Huey Lewis plays harmonica on Schoolgirl>Smokestack but other than that nothing to really write home about. The band hadn't played in a few months, in which time Jerry had got a new guitar and Weir had had surgery on his vocal chords. By no means a bad show, but was pretty much a soundcheck/warm-up for the stunning performance they played the following night.
Smokin show This show has been a favorite for a while, good to find such a GREAT copy. Promised Land smokes, keys are awesome and the China>Rider is what I always remember.
SOTM What are you kidding me?? This is by far the best SOTM ever. Listen to the jam at the end, its comparable to the best Dew out there! Jerry goes crazy on the end jam. Listen again.

Absolute BEST SOTM Ever!!! There really is not a SOTM out there that compares.  Garcia goes off at the end!!  Chills are everywhere whenever I put it on.  The SOTM from 6/7/91 is probably the second best and its not even in the same ballpark!!
First set is short but the second set makes up for it.

nice it is special to me...this site, the show, and the recording all coming together nicely here....my little 2 and a half year old boy kickin back with a lollipop listening to lazy river road {superb quality, jerry not missing a word!}     good times man!!!
The Oregon Trail Mix Does anyone have a copy of "The Oregon Trail Mix" that was played over the sound system just befor the boys opened up with Here Comes Sunshine?

Arrival of Bolt A great couple shows. Sound quality is superb SBD. Jerry seems experimental and curious, which I think is driven by his new axe. One of the best sound quality shows out there. The next day's show is as equally great - Bob passing time waiting for Jer's guitar to kick back in.

Summer 93' After a decent summer tour it was nice seeing the band in top form and good spirts at these pair of shows. Bobby had his voice back and  Garcia had a new guitar. The best post Brent China -Rider.

Old glory standing stiffly... As far as shows from '93 go, this one's a keeper.  Great SOTM.  

Query:  Huey Lewis??

Best Standing On The Moon If you're here, it's likely because you're drawn to the later era Standing on the Moons. This one is the first where Jerry would bring back the "be with you" lyric after the monster end solo (mantra style). It wouldn't be the last, but this is the first and best version played that way. June 2nd 1995 is also a classic SOTM. 9/10/91 provides the SOTM gold standard. This song is one of my favorites (a 90's If I Had The World To Give, if you will) and the lyrics are so deep and beautiful. This is one of those lyrics where Hunter hits home on hundreds of levels. The meaning of this song has evolved over time for me, it's been about just about everything at one point, my ex-girl friend, my newly departed father, my home. Ever been surrounded by beauty and joy but would trade it all to hold hands for just a minute with your beloved? This is your tune. In 2005, I came across this Rubens, with Mary as the Woman of the Apocalypse, standing on the moon, and my jaw dropped. Go see this at the Getty if you are in or near L.A. Be with you. Be with you.

SOTM I was at this show, and didn't realize it at
the time, but this is probably the BEST Standing
On The Moon EVER!!! It has such power and emotion
and it builds and builds seemingly forever. I put
it up there with Morning Dew from Cornell '77...
Great China>Rider.....

no cobwebs Awesome quality soundboard--5 stars

Tight show, this show is a good example of Jerry Garcia riding the crest of his health "renaissance" of late 92-early 94...

This show is also the debut of Rosebud

Bird Song and China>Rider are delivered in authoritative and jammed out fashion.  In the second set, Standing On The Moon is the big highlight of the show and is one of the Hall of Fame versions out there...Garcia breaks out the washboard during the coda and takes it to a new level...For S.O.T.M. fans, check out 03-16-94 and 12-06-1989 for other titanic versions...Saturday Night wraps up the set...

Best China Cat - Rider EVER! I am a bassist and I love the dead. They definitely were the best band ever!  In touch with their times, but at the same time, way ahead of their time. I belive this show contains the best China Cat Rider ever - and that's saying a lot because I've heard a lot of them in my time.  It's almost magical.  Jerry must have been very close to enlightenment throughout and he's own fire in RIder, but at the same time, he is giving it his unimitatable feeling in every note.  Phil crushes Rider too.  And the vibe effect on keys adds a lot to the overall sound.  I prabably have listened to this combo 5000 times and it is still as fresh in its feeling as it was the first time - truly one of those Dead gems that you stumble onto that leave an indelible impact on you about the band's greatness.
Download it and be with them.
Peace!

Sunburnt in Oregan Great show the sun was perty darn hot that day and so was the band. Although Huey Lewis is barley audible in the mix its a excellent source. Illegal source was obtained through me and gratefully liberated to the masses by Jay Serafin..THANKS JAY!!! 5 stars for sound quality 4 for energy

I Fought the Law I had a peak experience during the "I Fought the Law." Absolutley the pinnacle of the Grateful Dead experience, along with Dark Star 2/13/70, Other One 5/2/70, It's a Sin 6/28/74, Morning Dew 9/17/87 and Wave to the Wind 5/22/93. Although that particular Wave to the Wind may be the best thing those boys ever did, period!!

Hot show  In U OREGON this was the show that i met my wife at it only took 23 years too meet my dead head wife a mexican girl of my dreams too get to the show was great Here comes sunshine Queen Jane bird song all points pointing to my new wife Truckin to find my Bride i lived in San Diego She lived in Chico  then the last time hot and a sat daynight to end my dream night and weve been marryed 10 years
To  realrovingsign: Wave To The Wind was not played at Shoreline 5-22-93...You might be thinking about the Next Night...

lightning bolt's first appearance Correct me if I am wrong, but isn't this the first show for the Lightning Bolt? 

Great Sound.

fair to middlin High quality SBD sound. Not the most transplendent and inspiring show, but worthwhile.
A 3.5 of 5 on the Kind-o-meter.

Dark Star-like deconstruction during Bird Song jam - but they bungle some of the regularly occuring components.

Interesting sound effects/keys following Bobby's main guitar part on China Cat. Sloppy jam/transition to Rider

Interesting 2nd set. To Vince's credit - "Space" certainly evolved another step forward during his tenure.

sotm Fantastic version. One reviewer compares it to a 90's version of If i had the World to Give. I totally see that and would have loved for that tune to have been in the post space slot.

First set is well, nothing. Second set has some nice moments. But the SOTM is a beast.

My best show ever! It was a blazing hot show both weather wise and as an experience! Had an out of body experience that peaked during Space - wow - never had anything like that before or since. Would have liked to stay for the next night's awesome show, but started the road trip back to Spokane afterwards. Eugene was always magic!

Thanks for the memories Boy did I have a great time at this show. Every time I look back at the pictures, I get goosebumps. I had a huge group of friends, including ony of my best friends' mom, who hadn't seen the dead in years, and everything just came together beautifully. 

The opener with the pure vocals on "Here comes sunshine" just set the tone for the whole weekend, and the SOTM just lifted the whole stadium into the Oregon Sky and flew off. 

Fantastic, this was probably the funnest weekend I've ever had.

My first shows Eugene 93 were my first dead shows.  I had a decent tape collection by then so I was down enough to get the significance of Jerry's SOTM performance.  It was unforgettable.  Tis hard to write a review and Sunday's show on the 22nd was a MONSTER but this review is for the SOTM.  

Who can forget the chills of that first experience hearing the fat man at his best...taking the crowd to a level of euphoric insanity.  Bending his knees, pushing his vocals to the limit, shredding the guitar, (BE WITH YOU!) what a sight to see and hear a man so chill take it up a couple of notches.  GDAMN i miss the GD.

I remember the perfect sun, the stadium filled to the rim with 50K crazies, the giant sets of speakers at midfield, marshmallows melting on the turf like my (sober) 19 year old mind during his first ride on the bus.  IF ONLY I'd been born a little earlier in time I'd have caught a 100 shows.

Ah i recall the stupid smile on my face waking up the next morning on somebody's floor knowing the dead were playin' again.  You just KNEW sunday would be unreal.  

And I thought The Maker in Seattle two weeks prior (JGB) was a religious experience.  

Turn it up!  Thank you archive, thank you thank you

excellent sound, ok show the SOTM is HOT! schoolgirl>smokestack is interesting for its rarity in the later days, but I have to say, it's always tough to hear it. Makes me yearn for the older days when those tunes SMOKED!

but yeah, this one's not bad if you like the 90s.
nice Very nice show, worth the download!!

Autzen Stadium-SOTM I was so excited I found this on IA- my SBD tape got eaten a few months ago and this show totally rocked.  I agree that SOTM was amazing- Jerry had a great time with this one, and it shows in the sound on this SBD.  It was my first west coast show, and well worth the trip from Colorado.  The Indigo Girls weren't bad either!!  Thanks for letting me hear this show again when I thought I wever would!  I'm just bummed I can't record it for my trips in the car!

93 at it's finest MAN... after reading all the "first set was short" comments, I have to wonder what you people weren't smoking before you listened to it.....  
you guys aren't giving that set the credit it deserves...... Who cares how short it was as long as it was right on and right on it was.. 
This was one of the best first sets of the 90's.... 
 Other ther than the standard promisedland, this set one is easily one of my all time favorites and I am the 70's 80's type...I very rarely listen to vince stuff But the Bird Song from this show is the best version I have ever heard, live or recorded.... and the Lazy River and Queen Jane are JUST as perfect....   So remember that even though longer is usually better, that was not the case on this day.

I Hella Heart Autzen! what an epic recording!! 
soooo crisp and clean..brings me right back to that crystal-clear, and VERY HOT day in Eugene...
absolutely flipped over this first set and love all the freakyness of Micky and Vince in Drums-> Space, but,whoa..maybe a little toooo much panning by the board!!! careful when wearing phones!..lol

*this was only my second show, and truly unaware of the historic SOTM that went down..i grew up a huge Clash fan and freaked when they busted out 'I Fought The Law'!! a great day indeed.. 

**I love this site and appreciate all the knowledge and input all ya'll put into the mixes and show reviews!
great first set it is indeed short, but very entertaining

Maybe my favorite 93 show The scene around Autzen was a deadhead paradise--camping, vending, and freaking freely in the warm sun.  My first west coast show.  I think the dead came on at 2 in the afternoon.  I love this China/Rider, maybe my favorite of the Vince era.  Standing On The Moon was pure church as the crowd reveled in Jerry's impassioned playing and vocals at the closing jam.  Give it a listen you will not be disappointed.  One of the best ever!  Huey Lewis joined them for Smokestack/Schoolgirl.  I Fought The Law was still new enough that it wasn't a total downer (although the vocals on this version are truly awful).  At first glance the set list may not look too impressive, but they played with precision, focus, and heart.  No "Jerryatrics" whatsoever!  The next night was also great, but I prefer this one.  I used to have a crisp audience tape of this show and I pretty much wore it out.  93 is definitely not my favorite year, but this show is a jewel.  Hard to believe it was almost 20 years ago.....

Great show & great atmosphere Indeed the greatest show and experience of the 90's for me. As the previous reviewer noted, the town was full of dead folk and the locals were outstanding. It was the closest thing to woodstock I've ever experienced.

On fire!! I celebrated my 6th birthday during this concert, so it hold special significance for me :-) Unlike most of their other "August 21st" concerts (excepting the very mellow 1972 Berkley performance) this one is really fantastic. I'm especially impressed with the guitar playing here: Jerry is remarkably tight for such a late concert in the band's history. 

I always considered the concerts after 1991 to be weaker, but this performance clearly demonstrates that GD was still very capable of putting out a barn-burner even in the final years. "I Fought The Law" and Vince's strong vocals on "Way To Go Home" stick out for being more rare songs. Eugene must have been giving off some very positive energy levels!
Down The Middle Highlights: Way To Go Home

autzen 8-21 1993 These two at Autzen were some of the finest friend, wife, and I ever saw-with over 300 under the belt
The best Standing on the Moon
Normally my wife and I always "watched" the shows with our eyes closed
But as Jerry was finishing "Standing" my buddy said to us-"You gotta see Jerry"
Garcia almost went to his knees finishing the song!
Don't miss the 8-22 opener-Jack Straw
Jerry must have played with Steve Kimmock the night before after Zero's show at the Hilton
"There is nothing like a Grateful Dead show"

Not that great I'm not a fan of this first set.  At least not this recording.  HCS is a muddle.  Jerry picks up some steam towards the end, though.  The sound finally improves during Walking Blues.  LRR is just a milquetoast, inoffensive, laid-back, easy-listening tune.  Queen Jane builds some energy for the first time.  Bird Song is a bit disappointing, though.  Vince is missing for a long stretch of it, and Bob's doing -- whatever Bob does.  It's dissonant and doesn't fit with Jerry, who's just playing standard modal lead guitar.  Promised Land is pretty standard.  

China>Rider is a good solid start to the second set, but then we get yet another "Long Way to Hear This."  They were pushing it hard in 92-93, but it's just a bad song, badly sung.  Jerry tries to liven it up a bit, but when I heard this song, I just wanted it to be over quickly.  "Long, long, long, long ...," yeah, ok, whatever.  

Next comes Truckin'>somethin'>somethin'.  That usually meant a stretch of pretty boring music in the 90's.  Sad, because Truckin' once was a major jam vehicle.  Here, the "somethin's" are Schoolgirl>Smokestack.  This medley is a bit hotter than usual, though, with a guest harmonica player and with Jerry pretty well energized.  There are some definite Other One sounds just before Drums.  

Sadly, though, it's (Wish It Was) The Last Time out of Space.  That's followed, though, by the best song of the night.  This must have been about the time Jerry started to really go all out on SOTM, because the '92 version I heard was terrible, but this one just burns!  Not much to say about the end of the show.

BEEEEEE WITH YOUUUUU Above average 90's show that happens to feature the greatest Standing on the Moon ever played, Jerry gives it his all on the tune and the rest is history.

For a show in 1993 this is as good as it gets. A must hear for deadheads venturing into the later years.
Great Show, Great setting Grateful Phishmon has no soul
